04551nam a22005655i 9780822378891DE-B159720201125033335.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||201125t20142014ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808223788917 a10.1515/97808223788912doi  a(DE-B1597)554712  a(OCoLC)868989860  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC 4aHM841b.G3713 2014 7aSOC0020102bisacsh04a303.48/22231 aGarcía Canclini, Néstor, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aImagined Globalization /cNéstor García Canclini. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[2014] 4c©2014  a1 online resource (288 p.) :b14 color illustrations  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aLatin America in Translation00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tTranslator's Introduction -- tIntroduction Culture and Politics in the Imaginaries of Globalization -- tPart I Narratives, metaphors, and theories -- tOne Globalize or Defend Identity: How to Get Out of This Binary -- tTwo Globalization: An Unidentified Cultural Object -- tThree Market and Interculturality: Latin America between Europe and the United States -- tFour We Don't Know What to Call Others -- tPart II Interlude -- tFive Disagreements between a Latin American Anthropologist, a European Sociologist, and a U.S. Cultural Studies Scholar -- tPart III Policies for interculturality -- tSix From Paris to Miami via Nueva York -- tSeven Capitals of Culture and Global Cities -- tEight Toward a Cultural Agenda of Globalization -- tNine Toward an Anthropology of Misunderstandings: A Methodological Discussion on Interculturality -- tEpilogue Social and Imaginary Changes in Globalization Today -- tReferences -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aA leading figure in cultural studies worldwide, Néstor García Canclini is a Latin American thinker who has consistently sought to understand the impact of globalization on the relations between Latin America, Europe, and the United States, and among Latin American countries. In this book, newly available in English, he considers how globalization is imagined by artists, academics, migrants, and entrepreneurs, all of whom traverse boundaries and, at times, engage in conflicted or negotiated multicultural interactions.García Canclini contrasts the imaginaries of previous migrants to the Americas with those who live in transnational circuits today. He integrates metaphor and narrative, working through philosophical, anthropological, and socioeconomically grounded interpretations of art, literature, crafts, media, and other forms of expression toward his conclusion that globalization is, in important ways, a collection of heterogeneous narratives. García Canclini advocates global imaginaries that generate new strategies for dealing with contingency and produce new forms of citizenship oriented toward multiple social configurations rather than homogenization. This edition of Imagined Globalization includes a significant new introduction by George Yúdice and an interview in which the cultural theorist Toby Miller and García Canclini touch on events including the Arab Spring and Occupy Wall Street.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 25. Nov 2020) 0aAcculturation. 0aGlobalizationxSocial aspects. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh1 aYúdice, George08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDUK eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311071182040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780822378891zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780822378891423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780822378891.jpg  a978-3-11-071182-0  DUK eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aEBA_DUK_ALL  aEBA_DUK_EALL  aEBA_DUK_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles